[2] UK (Exeter)
Date: Sat 24 Sep 2011
Source: Xmedia online [abbreviated & edited]
http://xmedia.ex.ac.uk/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=118:student-measles-outbreak-feared-by-the-health-protection-agency&catid=6:news&Itemid=13


The University of Exeter and health experts are urging students to
ensure before that when they attend university they have been
vaccinated against measles. Suspicion of a future outbreak of the
infection has been confirmed by data from the Health Protection Agency
(HPA), which shows that the number of measles cases this year [2011]
has more than doubled the complete number of cases of measles
infection from last year.

There were 777 cases of measles by the end of July this year [2011] in
comparison to just 374 measles infections for the entire 2010 period.
The largest number of cases has been among young adults under the age
of 25, which has led the HPA to consider new outbreaks of the measles
infection likely as students return to campuses across the country.
The organisation also stated that the cases confirmed so far amongst
this age group were associated with small groups of people in
universities and schools where many of the attendees had not been
vaccinated against the infection.

The University of Exeter Student Guild is also urging new or returning
students attending the campus this autumn season to check with their
GPs as to whether they have been vaccinated against measles. The Guild
also advises that if a student has not been vaccinated against the
infection, they should be aware of the initial symptoms of the illness
and are urged that if concerned that they may have the infection to
contact their GP or the Student Health Centre.

[Byline: Amanda Hughes]

