[3] UK (HPA)
Date: Sat 25 Sep 2011
Source: The Telegraph [abridged & edited]
http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/8776987/European-measles-outbreak-spreads-to-Britain.html


The Health Protection Agency (HPA) has released figures showing that
across England and Wales, there were 777 laboratory-confirmed cases in
the 1st 7 months of 2010, compared to 374 for all of 2010. In the 1st
7 months of 2010, there were 208 confirmed cases.

Most of those affected have been children and young adults. In many
cases, the sources of local outbreaks are thought to have been people
who travelled to Europe on holiday. France, Spain, Germany and
Switzerland have experienced major outbreaks this year [2011], each
recording thousands of cases. All saw immunisation rates for the
measles, mumps and rubella (MMR) vaccine plummet after 1998, when The
Lancet published a small study linking it with autism and bowel
disorders.

The study has since been comprehensively dismissed as seriously
flawed. Immunisation rates in Britain have only recently recovered,
earlier this year [2011] breaking the 90 per cent mark for the 1st
time in 13 years. The legacy of the Lancet study means many older
children and young people remain unprotected, as they never received
the vaccine. Two jabs are required to offer full protection. They are
usually given at a year and about 3.5 years, although they can be
given in 2 stages to older children and adults.

Dr Mary Ramsay, the HPA's head of the immunisation, said: "Measles and
meningitis are infections that can both be fatal; it is absolutely
vital that all students [entering universities] ensure they are
completely up to date with all their vaccinations, especially the MMR
and Men C vaccine. University bars and campuses where lots of students
are in close proximity are ideal places for bacteria and viruses to
spread, which is why we may see more outbreaks of these infections in
this environment."

[Byline: Stephen Adams]

