The Americas
------------
[5] Canada (Quebec)
Date: Thu 22 Sep 2011
Source: CTV Montreal [abbreviated & edited]
http://montreal.ctv.ca/servlet/an/local/CTVNews/20110922/mtl_measles_110922/20110922/?hub=MontrealHome


For the 1st time since 2007, Quebec is dealing with a wide scale
measles outbreak. More than 700 cases of the potentially deadly
disease have been reported in the province this year [2011], with the
majority of people being infected between April and July 2011,
although new infections are still being reported. Most of the people
infected live in the Mauricie region of the province, but the most
recent cases have been reported in the Eastern Townships.

Twelve percent of the infections have been so bad people needed to be
hospitalized for treatment. Measles can cause blindness, encephalitis,
pneumonia and death. Public health officials suspect the disease was
brought into Quebec by European visitors. They are urging parents to
get children vaccinated against the disease.

Vaccination rates against measles have dropped since 1998, when a
medical researcher faked research and falsely claimed there was a link
between a measles vaccine and autism. That research has since been
thoroughly discredited; the journal that published the study has
apologized, and the doctor involved has been stripped of his medical
license.

