[9] NZ (Bay of Plenty)
Date: Sat 24 Sep 2011
Source: Sunlive [abbreviated & edited]
http://www.sunlive.co.nz/news/16683-measles-outbreak-spreads.html


Bay of Plenty health officials are urging people to check whether they
are immunised against measles, as an outbreak of the disease continues
to spread nationally.

In the last week, there has been a surge in the number of people
infected with the disease, with 45 reported cases, including one in
the Bay of Plenty, taking the total number of confirmed cases since
May 2011 to 167 [nationally].

Bay of Plenty District Health Board medical officer of health Dr Phil
Shoemack says people should be getting their children immunised and be
aware of coming into contact with anyone if they, or their children,
are not immunised. Vaccination is the best way to protect against
measles with the Measles-Mumps-Rubella (MMR) vaccine available, given
in 2 doses, normally at 15 months and 4 years of age.

Dr Shoemack says the immunisation rate in the Bay of Plenty is
improving, although it has not reached the 95 per cent target.

The number of cases in New Zealand is continuing to grow, particularly
in the Auckland region, where 27 contacts are currently in quarantine.
Health officials say many people have come into contact with the
measles on domestic flights and are warning anyone who is planning to
travel to check their immunisation status 1st.

Dr Shoemack says there has been one confirmed case of the measles in
the Bay of Plenty, and that was an overseas visitor who is now back in
their home country.

[Byline: Phillipa Yalden]

